When a verification target is located in a free (or a library) function, it is checked multiple times in the context of all the contracts.
When the verification target is safe for one contract, but unsafe for another, the model checker can report both answers.

Consider this example:
```solidity
function check(uint x) pure {
    assert(x > 0);
}

contract C {
    function a() public pure {
        check(1);
    }
}

contract D {
    function b(uint x) public pure {
        check(x);
    }
}
```

Running `solc --model-checker-engine chc --model-checker-show-proved-safe` reports
```shell
Warning: CHC: Assertion violation happens here.
Counterexample:

x = 0

Transaction trace:
D.constructor()
D.b(0)
    multi.sol:check(0) -- internal call
 --> multi.sol:2:5:
  |
2 |     assert(x > 0);
  |     ^^^^^^^^^^^^^

Info: CHC: Assertion violation check is safe!
 --> multi.sol:2:5:
  |
2 |     assert(x > 0);
  |     ^^^^^^^^^^^^^
```

I believe that if the target can be violated in the context of at least one contract, only the violation should be reported.

